{{italic title}}
The '''''Chanyuan qinggui''''' ({{zh|t=禪苑清規|w=Ch'an-yüan ch'ing-kuei|p=Chányuàn qīngguī}}; {{CJKV|k=Sōnwōn chō'nggyu|j=禅苑清規, Zenen Shingi|v=Thiền Uyển Thanh Quy}}) or '''''The Rules of Purity in the Chan Monastery''''', is a highly influential set of rules for [[Zen]] monasteries compiled by the Chinese monk [[Changlu Zongze]] in 1103. Although many other monastic codes aimed at the Zen school would follow, ''Chanyuan qinggui'' is the oldest extant work of its kind. Prior to the ''Rules of Purity'', various translations of Indian [[Vinaya]] texts had existed in China since the fifth century, while Chinese monks beginning with [[Daoan]] has created [[Sangha (Buddhism)|sangha]] regulations in the 4th century. However, none was extensive or geared towards any particular sect that existed at that time. Both types of regulations has a direct influence on ''Chanyuan qinggui'', but neither aimed to be nearly as extensive or authoritative. The text regulates nearly all aspects of daily life in a monastery, from the proper protocol for ceremonies to the correct way to visit the toilet. The text became the standard reference for its topic not only in [[Song Dynasty]] China, but also well into the [[Yuan Dynasty]], as well as abroad in Korea and Japan.<ref>{{citation|last=Yifa|year=2002|title=The origins of Buddhist monastic codes in China: an annotated translation and study of the Chanyuan qinggui|isbn=0824824946|publisher=University of Hawaii Press|place=Honolulu|page=xix-xxii}}</ref>

