{{Refimprove|date=March 2015}} {{Use dmy dates|date=March 2015}} '''Friedrich Dessauer''' (19 July 1881 &ndash; 16 February 1963) was a physicist, a philosopher, a socially engaged entrepreneur and a journalist.
Friedrich Dessauer was born in [[Aschaffenburg]], [[Germany]]. As a young man he was fascinated by new discoveries in the natural sciences. He was particularly interested in the [[X-rays]] discovered by [[Wilhelm Röntgen|Röntgen]] and their medical applications. Dessauer studied at the Goethe University in [[Frankfurt am Main]] until 1917. From 1924 to 1933 he was a [[Centre Party (Germany)|Zentrum]] party member of the Reichstag, the German Parliament.<ref name="mitcham">{{cite book |last=Mitcham |first=C. |title=Thinking through technology: the path between engineering and philosophy |publisher=University of Chicago Press |year=1994 |isbn=978-0-226-53198-4 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hN2rCvAUF4cC&pg=PA29 |page=29 }}</ref>
Born into a [[Jewish]] family,<ref>Abraham Myerson & Isaac Goldberg, ''The German Jew: his share in modern culture'', A. A. Knopf (1933), p. 77</ref><ref>Stanford J. Shaw, ''The Jews of the Ottoman Empire and the Turkish Republic'', Springer (2016), p. 253</ref> he was imprisoned by the Nazis when they came to power for his opposition to Hitler. He was released at request of the [[Turkey|Turkish]] government, who invited him to the [[University of Istanbul]], where he was made chair of the Institute. Here he worked together with [[Erich Uhlmann]] to develop medical applications of X-rays in Turkey. He moved to [[Fribourg University]] in 1937 to become the chair of experimental physics.<ref>{{cite book |last=Reisman |first=A. |title=Turkey's Modernization: Refugees from Nazism and Atatürk’s Vision. |year=2006 |page=208 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=coks7vEqZT8C&pg=PA208 |publisher=New Academia Publishers |isbn=0-9777908-8-6 }}</ref>
On 16 February 1963 Dessauer died from radioactive contamination.<ref name="mitcham"/> His name was added to the ''[[Monument to the X-ray and Radium Martyrs of All Nations]]'' in [[Hamburg]], Germany.
