'''Michiel van Lambalgen''' (born 6 November 1954, [[Krimpen aan den IJssel]]) is a professor of [[Logic]] and [[Cognitive Science]] at the [[Institute for Logic, Language and Computation]] and the Department of Philosophy, [[University of Amsterdam]] in the [[Netherlands]].<ref>See his [http://staff.science.uva.nl/~michiell/ web page] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070527085904/http://staff.science.uva.nl/~michiell/ |date=2007-05-27 }}.</ref>
In the 1980s van Lambalgen did research in randomness,<ref>[http://staff.science.uva.nl/~michiell/docs/fFDiss.pdf Random sequences] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060529034608/http://staff.science.uva.nl/~michiell/docs/fFDiss.pdf |date=2006-05-29 }}. Unpublished PhD dissertation, Department of Mathematics and Computer Science, University of Amsterdam, 1987.</ref> but after some time felt the subject was "too abstract". Then in the 1990s he moved to [[artificial intelligence]], where he picked up the methodology for studying cognition. In 1999 he spent a sabbatical with [[Keith Stenning]] at the [[University of Edinburgh]] where he learned about the [[psychology of reasoning]].<ref>See the [http://www.kent.ac.uk/secl/philosophy/jw/TheReasoner/vol2/TheReasoner-2(9).pdf interview] with van Lambalgen in [http://www.thereasoner.org/ The Reasoner].</ref> His research interests include philosophy and the foundations of mathematics, reasoning with uncertainty, the psychology of reasoning, and the cognitive semantics of natural language.<ref>See [http://staff.science.uva.nl/~michiell/docs/CVMvL.pdf his CV] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110606062449/http://staff.science.uva.nl/~michiell/docs/CVMvL.pdf |date=2011-06-06 }}.</ref>
