[[File:Nagasaki Sofukuji M5564.jpg|left|thumb|Sōfuku-ji's Daiippōmon]]The [[Obaku (school of Buddhism)|Ōbaku school]] of Zen arrived in Japan in the middle of the seventeenth century, several centuries after the other Zen schools, and as a consequence its temples typically have a different architecture, based on Chinese [[Ming Dynasty|Ming]] and [[Qing Dynasty|Qing]] architectures.<ref name="niho35">Nishi, Hozumi (1996:35)</ref>
A great example of the style is [[Manpuku-ji]] in Uji, near Kyoto, whose main building, the Daiyūhōden, was built in 1668.
Another important Ōbaku temple is [[Sōfuku-ji (Nagasaki)|Sōfuku-ji]], built in 1629 in Nagasaki by Chinese immigrants.<ref name="niho35"/> The Daiippō[[Mon (architecture)|mon]], a [[National Treasures of Japan|National Treasure]], was built in 1644 by Chinese carpenters.<ref>{{Jaanus2|d/daiippoumon|Daiippoumon|4-14-11}}</ref> Rebuilt in 1694 with material imported from China, it is one of the best examples of the style.<ref name="niho35"/> Painted in typically Chinese [[polychromy]], it has four-step brackets ("[[tokyō]]") in the front and back, and ordinary three-step brackets on the sides.<ref name="niho35"/>
